UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304405X89900056
AB  - This study examines the variance of returns on common stocks around the time exchange-traded options are listed on these stocks. The evidence indicates that stock return variance declines after options listing, and that this phenomenon is not fully explained by contemporaneous shifts in market volatility. In addition, stock market trading volume increases, on average, after options are listed on firms' stocks. I examine the hypothesis that the variance changes are related to changes in ‘trading noise” in the stock, but find little direct support for this explanation.
